{
  "nbformat": 4,
  "nbformat_minor": 5,
  "metadata": {
    "kernelspec": {
      "name": "maxima",
      "display_name": "Maxima",
      "language": "maxima"
    },
    "aximar": {}
  },
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "# 06 — Reinforcement learning a MagLev controller\n\nA steel ball is suspended below an electromagnet by an attractive force $\\propto i^2 / x^2$, fighting gravity. Open-loop the system is *unstable*: drop the current and the ball falls; raise it slightly and the ball slams into the magnet. A controller has to keep the ball at a target distance below the magnet using only position feedback.\n\nThis notebook does the same control problem **three ways** against the same Modelica plant:\n\n1. **Pole placement**: linearise around the equilibrium with `mod_state_space`, choose where the closed-loop poles should go, solve for the gains.\n2. **LQR**: linearise, supply quadratic state and input penalty matrices, get the optimal gains in one shot via `mod_lqr`.\n3. **Reinforcement learning**: black-box optimise the same PD gains with `np_cem` (cross-entropy method) directly against the *nonlinear* plant — no linearisation, no operating-point assumption.\n\nThe interesting comparison is what each method gets you. Pole placement and LQR both work on the linearised plant but ask different questions of the engineer; CEM treats the simulator as a black box and tunes against actual nonlinear dynamics, including the inverse-square magnetic-force term.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "load(\"../../mochi.mac\")$\nload(\"numerics\")$\nload(\"numerics-sundials\")$\nload(\"numerics-learn\")$\nload(\"../../mochi-nonlinear.mac\")$\nload(\"ax-plots\")$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 47,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 1. The plant\n\n$$m\\,\\ddot{x} = m g - \\frac{k_m i^2}{x^2}$$\n\nwhere $x$ is the ball's distance below the magnet (positive downward), $i$ is the coil current, and $k_m$, $m$, $g$ are constants. The bias current $i_{\\text{bias}}$ is the value at which gravity exactly balances the magnetic force at the setpoint $x_{\\text{ref}}$:\n\n$$i_{\\text{bias}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{m g x_{\\text{ref}}^2}{k_m}}$$\n\nIt's declared as a *parameter-of-parameters* in `MagLev.mo`; mochi's fixed-point resolver folds the expression to a number.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "m : mod_load(\"../MagLev.mo\")$\nmod_print(m)$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 48,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Model:  MagLev\n  parameters:\n              [[ball_mass,0.02],[grav,9.81],[km,1.6e-4],[x_ref,0.008],\n               [i_bias,sqrt((ball_mass*grav)/km)*abs(x_ref)]]\n  states:      [x,v]\n  derivs:      [der_x,der_v]\n  inputs:      [coil_i]\n  outputs:     [y]\n  initial:     [[x,0.011],[v,0.0]]\n  residuals:\n     der_x-v  = 0\n     (coil_i^2*km)/(ball_mass*x^2)-grav+der_v  = 0\n     y-x  = 0"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## 2. Open-loop check: the ball falls\n\nWith `coil_i = 0` the magnetic force vanishes; the ball just free-falls. We start it slightly below the setpoint at $x_0 = 0.011$ m.",
      "metadata": {}
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": "[t_open, x_open] : mod_simulate_nonlinear(\n    m, [0.011, 0.0], lambda([t], [0.0]), 0.05,\n    ['return = 'states, 'dt = 0.0005])$\n\nax_draw2d(\n  color=\"red\", line_width=2, name=\"x(t), no current\",\n  lines(t_open, map(first, x_open)),\n  color=\"black\", dash=\"dot\",\n  explicit(0.008, t, 0, 0.05),\n  title=\"Open-loop free fall (no coil current)\",\n  xlabel=\"t (s)\", ylabel=\"x (m, positive = below magnet)\",\n  yrange=[0, 0.04],\n  grid=true, showlegend=true)$",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": 49,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "data": {
            "application/x-maxima-plotly": [
